    "summary": "NO on Option B — if shortening, Option A is better",
    "content": "NO, but I'll concede the battle on shortening since I'm clearly outvoted there. My concern remains: \"character\" alone is ambiguous in running text.\n\nThat said, if shortening is happening regardless, then Option B is worse than Option A. The parenthetical \"(constitutive)\" format is typographically awkward and philosophically self-undermining — it introduces a qualifier while simultaneously apologizing for it. It says \"this word matters but also please ignore it.\" That's not how you establish a technical term.\n\nIf we must shorten: go with Option A. Introduce \"constitutive character (德 De)\" with full authority at first occurrence, explain in a TN that subsequent occurrences use \"character\" as shorthand, and let the reader do the work. At least that way the full term has dignity at introduction rather than arriving pre-deprecated."
  }
}
